  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Thread of Life: Mayan Families Rescuing Ancestral Traditions in South Yucatan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project covers six population groups in southern Yucat&#xE1;n. These families live under conditions of poverty, social marginalization, under-nutrition and loss of cultural values and natural resources. 385 families and 60 individuals will participate, receiving beehives, local-breed hogs, worms, fruit trees, seeds and poultry. The participating families will improve their living conditions by eating and marketing healthful produce, recovering their Mayan traditions and ancient ceremonies regarding agriculture, to maintain their ethnic identity and value Nature. This project will contribute to recovering two endemic animals of great cultural importance: hairy hogs and stingless bees, which are in a vulnerable situation because of environmental deterioration and introduced species. They are species that the Mayan people know how to raise, to produce food and medicine without spending much money. The project activities reinforce the work that the Small-Farmer School, U Yits Kaan, has been doing in the region for 16 years.</narrative>
  </description>
